Introduction
------------

Midnight Commander (also referred to as MC) is a user shell with
text-mode full-screen interface.  It can be run on the OS console,
in xterm and other terminal emulators.

Midnight Commander allows you to manage files while making the most of
your screen and giving you a clear representation of the filesystem, yet
it's simple enough to be run over a telnet or ssh session.

This distribution is a modified fork of GNU Midnight Commander, based on
version 4.8.33 and maintained at:

* https://github.com/ilia-maslakov/mcdev

Changes since 2026-02.  It is not an official GNU package; please report
issues with this fork to the address in "Reporting problems" below, not
to the upstream project.

Midnight Commander is released under the GNU General Public License
version 3 or any later version.  A copy of the file is included with
this distribution package.


Dependencies
------------

Please read the file INSTALL for installation instructions
and full list of dependencies.


Features
--------

Midnight Commander was conceived as a free clone of John Socha's
Norton Commander (TM).  It also takes the best from more recent software
with similar interfaces.  Midnight Commander comes with mouse support
on xterm and optionally on the Linux console.

Some features are specific to the POSIX environment MC runs on, some are
familiar to the users of similar software for other operating systems.
The features include:

	* Built in Virtual File System: browse the contents of tar, ar,
	  rpm, zip, cpio, lha and rar archives just like local files, and
	  connect to remote machines over secure shell.  Remote FTP, SFTP,
	  S3, Samba and other services are provided by panel plugins (see
	  "Fork additions").

	* Almost all operations work with the virtual file system,
	  enabling you to do complex tasks, like viewing files inside
	  archives.

	* Mouse support on most terminal emulators for X Window System
	  as well as on the Linux console.

	* Learn Keys: Midnight Commander may be configured at run
	  time to support any kind of input keys for a given terminal,
	  making its operation possible even on most weird terminals.

	* Text and hex editors are available for you to use (hex editor
	  is a part of the viewer).

	* Hotlist allows you to keep a list of common visited locations,
	  including remote sites and directories inside archives.

	* Command completion: By pressing Alt-Tab in any place where a
	  filename or an executable are expected, Midnight Commander
	  will complete the name for you.  If you press Alt-Tab for the
	  second time, you get a list box with all possible completions.

	* Subshell support: Run your commands by a real shell
	  interpreter.  Midnight Commander interacts with bash,
	  tcsh and zsh to provide you with all of the facilities
	  available in your preferred shell.

	* Find file command can search for the file contents.

	* Background operations allow you to copy or move files on any
	  virtual file system while you do other tasks.

	* Emacs-like key bindings are used in all widgets.

	* Context dependent actions (open, view, edit) are available.

	* The built-in file viewer, together with the context dependent
	  actions is used to format man pages on the fly, coloring mail
	  messages and more.

	* The built-in editor supports syntax highlighting and external
	  actions, such as spell checking and formatting.


Fork additions
--------------

This fork adds the following on top of GNU Midnight Commander 4.8.33.
See the release notes for the full list:

* https://github.com/ilia-maslakov/mcdev/wiki/Releases

	* Panel plugins: panel contents can be supplied by a dynamically
	  loaded plugin.  Shipped plugins include git, docker, Kubernetes,
	  MongoDB, S3, FTP/FTPS, SFTP, Samba, systemd, shell connections,
	  External Panelize, and arcmc.  The old built-in ftpfs and sftpfs
	  VFS modules are removed in favour of the FTP and SFTP plugins.

	* arcmc: an archive manager built on libarchive that browses,
	  creates, packs and extracts archives (zip, 7z, tar.*, cpio),
	  with progress and cancel.

	* Editor plugins, plus code folding, an undo history browser and
	  a macro explorer in the editor.

	* Viewer: a structured tree mode for JSON, YAML, XML and HTML, a
	  grep-style live filter, ANSI colour and terminal replay, and
	  streaming of never-ending command output.

	* An embedded terminal widget that runs a shell inside the file
	  manager and keeps the panels in sync with its directory.

	* User-editable panel view modes, and dialogs for managing key
	  bindings and learning terminal keys.


Mini-documentation
------------------

These are hints for the text mode edition:

* Use the F-Keys for invoking the commands in the function key bar.
  If your terminal doesn't support F-keys, you can use the <ESC digit>
  sequence to invoke the corresponding F-digit key.

* Tab changes the current panel.

* All input lines have emacs-like key-bindings (command history is
  accessed through the M-p and M-n keys).

* The panels accept C-n, C-p for browsing the panel (like in Emacs).

* M-Enter copies the currently selected file name to the input line.

* M-Tab completes the current word (or tries to).

* The Virtual File System lets you browse in tar and compressed tar
  files as well as browsing remote machines over the shell file system.

* Please read the manual page.

You can access the whole documentation online with the F1 key,
although it's not as nice as the groff printed manual page :-)


